TeamTalk 5 SpamBot for Ubuntu
-------------------------------------------------------

The TeamTalk 5 SpamBot is a Pro-only moderation client that connects
to a TeamTalk Pro Server as a user account and watches for spam. It
can filter bad words in nicknames, status messages, channel names,
topics and text messages, detect login/join/kick floods from a single
IP address, ban known VPN networks, and consult AbuseIPDB for IP
reputation.

The SpamBot ships as a separate executable that authenticates with
BearWare.dk WebLogin, just like tt5prosrv. Without a valid Pro
WebLogin token the SpamBot will refuse to start.

The following sections explain how to:

- Run the Setup Wizard
- Configure BearWare.dk WebLogin
- Provide a Bad Words Dictionary
- Provide a VPN IP List
- Enable AbuseIPDB Integration
- Start the SpamBot
- Run the SpamBot as a Service


Run the Setup Wizard
--------------------

Once the SpamBot binary is in a writable working directory, run:

$ ./tt5spambot -wizard

The wizard walks through every configuration option and writes the
result to tt5spambot.xml in the current directory. The wizard can be
re-run at any time to adjust settings.

The wizard asks for:

- Server host address (default localhost), TCP and UDP port (default
  10333), and whether to use an encrypted connection (default no).
- Username, password and nickname (default "SpamBot") that the bot
  uses to log on to the target server. The account must exist on the
  Pro Server and should have ban/kick rights.
- Status message and gender (1=Male, 2=Female, 3=Neutral).
- Initial channel path. Leave it empty to let the server's
  UserAccount.szInitChannel decide which channel the bot joins.
- Toggles for each anti-spam feature: bad word filtering, abuse
  detection, VPN IP blocking, AbuseIPDB lookup and AbuseIPDB
  auto-report.
- Reconnect policy: maximum number of attempts (0 = retry forever)
  and the delay in seconds between attempts (default 10).


Configure BearWare.dk WebLogin
------------------------------

The SpamBot is gated by the same BearWare.dk WebLogin used by
tt5prosrv. The first time tt5spambot starts it will prompt for your
BearWare.dk username and password and offer to store the resulting
access token in tt5spambot.xml so subsequent runs are non-interactive.

The token can also be primed from the command line:

$ ./tt5spambot -weblogin user@bearware.dk:password

Once a token is stored the SpamBot will reuse it on startup. If the
password of the WebLogin account changes the stored token becomes
invalid and the SpamBot will prompt again.

If you already have a token (for example issued for another tool) you
can use it directly:

$ ./tt5spambot -tokenlogin user@bearware.dk:abcdef0123456789


Provide a Bad Words Dictionary
------------------------------

Bad word filtering loads every file in the configured directory whose
name matches the pattern "badwords*.txt". The language each file
covers is derived from its filename:

- badwords.txt              -> default language
- badwords_french.txt       -> french
- badwords_<lang>.txt       -> <lang>

Each file is a CSV list (one or more lines, each containing
comma-separated words). The Pro Portable package ships with
badwords.txt and badwords_french.txt as a starting point. Edit them
or drop additional badwords_<lang>.txt files alongside as needed.

In the wizard the "Directory to scan for badwords*.txt files" prompt
defaults to the current working directory. Use an absolute path if
the bot is launched from elsewhere (for example from systemd).


Provide a VPN IP List
---------------------

The SpamBot can ban networks known to host VPN exit nodes by reading
a plain text file with one IP-address or CIDR network per line. There
is no default path and the feature is disabled until you point the
wizard at a file.

A maintained list of VPN ranges is published by X4BNet:

  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/X4BNet/lists_vpn/main/output/vpn/ipv4.txt

Download it to a writable location, for example:

$ curl -o /home/tt/tt5spambot/vpnips.txt \
       https://raw.githubusercontent.com/X4BNet/lists_vpn/main/output/vpn/ipv4.txt

Then specify "/home/tt/tt5spambot/vpnips.txt" when the wizard asks
for the VPN IP list file path. The list is large and updated often;
schedule a cron job to keep it current, for example a daily refresh:

0 4 * * * curl -s -o /home/tt/tt5spambot/vpnips.txt \
          https://raw.githubusercontent.com/X4BNet/lists_vpn/main/output/vpn/ipv4.txt

Any file name and location works as long as the path matches the
wizard answer.


Enable AbuseIPDB Integration
----------------------------

AbuseIPDB integration has two independent toggles:

- IP reputation lookup: each incoming login is checked against
  AbuseIPDB; users whose IP exceeds the configured thresholds are
  kicked.
- Auto-report: users that the SpamBot bans for abuse are submitted
  back to AbuseIPDB as confirmed spammers.

Both features share a single API key, prompted only when at least one
of them is enabled. Sign up at https://www.abuseipdb.com to obtain a
key. The lookup thresholds (minimum total reports, distinct users and
confidence score) default to 2.


Start the SpamBot
-----------------

Once configured, start the SpamBot in the foreground with:

$ ./tt5spambot -nd -verbose

To run the bot as a daemon so the shell can exit:

$ ./tt5spambot -d


Run the SpamBot as a Service
----------------------------

A systemd unit and a System V init script are included in the Pro
Portable package under the spambot/systemd and spambot/init.d
directories. The unit is configured to start after tt5proserver so
the Pro Server is up before the bot tries to authenticate.

For systemd install the unit with:

$ sudo cp systemd/tt5spambot.service /etc/systemd/system/
$ sudo systemctl enable --now tt5spambot

For System V init copy the script and enable it:

$ sudo cp init.d/tt5spambot /etc/init.d/
$ sudo update-rc.d tt5spambot defaults

The shipped scripts assume the user "teamtalk" and a working
directory under /home/tt or /etc/teamtalk; adjust the paths as
needed for your installation.

